projectInfo.description:
Solidarités International is mapping with support from CartONG the Bandarban District in Bangladesh as part of an ECHO funded livelihoods and resilience programme. This ongoing programme intends to strengthen the resilience approach in Bandarban Hill Tracts, where humanitarian needs are high and very few other stakeholders provide support. Solidarités International and Action Contre la Faim are developing resilient WASH services and livelihoods to support the most vulnerable communities to reduce the risks and achieve disaster resilience.

Bangladesh is exposed to multiple natural hazards, and when combined with extreme poverty, this limits the ability of communities to recover from disasters. In Cox's Bazar, this has been aggravated by a recent influx of refugees. The core acute humanitarian needs have worsened due to the arrival of 72,300 new refugees since October 2017. While mainly residing in registered and makeshift camps, many new arrivals have settled in the host communities of Ukhiya and Teknaf and in connecting areas of the Bandarban Hill Tracts district for an indefinite period of time. As a consequence of these conditions, populations are at risk of protection issues and human-right abuses.

Data from the OSM maps will be essential for the operational teams to calculate populations’ estimates and analyze infrastructures’ coverage.

SI has been present Bangladesh since 2007, supporting populations to absorb, recover and adapt to natural disasters and displacement shocks. The Missing Maps project aims to map the most vulnerable places in the world (affected by humanitarian crises: disease epidemics, conflict, natural disasters, poverty, environmental crises). Building on HOT's disaster preparedness projects, the Missing Maps tasks facilitate pre-emptive mapping of priority countries to better facilitate disaster response, medical activities and resource allocation when crises occur.
